We said goodbye to my grandmother this week. 🤍 Joan McNaught, just two months shy of her 90th birthday. She was funny, sweet, and one of a kind. I think I get my dog obsession from her. 🐶😊

Grief is a complex emotion for anyone. While I know she was suffering and had been missing my grandfather for 13 years, I find myself grieving the missed opportunities. While I saw her somewhat regularly our relationship never seemed to go to a level of depth. I’ll be grieving the chance for that. I grieve it for my own mom, her daughter, too. 

I’m not a religious person but I am a spiritual one and I truly hope and pray that there can be a connection across the dimensions and that my grandparents are now reunited. Being that she was my mother’s last remaining parent, this feels like the end of an era but I hope it can also be the start of a new one, for her and my grandfather to live on through my family with a sense of peace & positive closure to our earthly relationships with them 💜

TW: suicide

We can’t pretend to know what was going on in tWitch’s mind or life, or anyone’s mind when they die by suicide. What I do know as a therapist and as a survivor of suicidal thoughts, is that the brain is an organ that can malfunction or become unstable like any other organ. Suicide does not say anything about a person’s character, love they felt for others, their strength, or personality. Suicide occurs when our brain chemistry is off. Actions are taken in a place far away from a sound mind. Suicide is a health epidemic that we MUST talk about if we want to see changes made.  Know the warning signs! For yourself, for others. Know that times of mental instability do not last forever and there is help, hope and support available.   If you or someone you know may be feeling this way- call 911 or 988.

A moment from each month of 2022 🤍

Twenty Twenty-Two 🤍
In sessions, I often ask clients to write and/or speak about their timelines. Making note of all of the significant events that took place in their lives, whether positive, negative or somewhere in between. 

In challenging myself to do the same today but for 2022 here’s what stuck out to me

✨I turned 30!
✨I traveled to Savannah and South Carolina several times
✨ I was diagnosed with adhd which has brought a lot of clarity 
✨ my disney annual pass ended- but our last trip was staying at the Animal Kingdom Lodge for the first time!
✨ I stood by the sides’ of two of my best friend’s on their biggest day, as a bridesmaid 
✨ My dad had a stroke two days before a planned family trip to Mexico.. it was a scary time and us “kids” still went on the trip, but to be honest with my anxiety levels I really didn’t enjoy the vacation. I am incredibly grateful my dad made it through and had a full recovery ❤️
✨ I counseled my ass off, and was the therapist in over 1,250 sessions 
✨I got my own office within the practice I work for, this was a big deal to no longer have to lug all my art supplies and games from room to room (I see a lot of kids & teens)
✨ two of my best childhood friends had their own babies! 🥰
✨ Went to Firefly and saw Avril Lavigne & MCR (both have been on my concert bucket list for a lonnng time)
✨ I did a ton of wedding planning
✨ Yuri became the first in his family to graduate from college 🥹
✨ I saw Dear Evan Hansen & Hamilton
✨ My grandmother passed away 🖤
✨ I found my wedding dress! & met Pnina Tornai
✨ I read or listened to a bunch of books
✨ I continue to have such wonderful, amazing friends, family, fiancé, dogs and clients and feel so grateful ❤️

Looking forward to a healthy and happy 2023 with a focus on
✨ Becoming a whole wife 😳
✨ Reprioritizing my own health, physically and mentally 
✨ Gaining a better work/life balance
✨ Saving more money
✨ Being a better friend, family member and partner
✨ Getting better at answering messages in a timely manner 🙈
✨ Looking into ways to expand my knowledge & share that knowledge on mental health & well being

My grandfather (my Fafa) is going to be 90 this Sunday. His health hasn't been the greatest lately, so naturally he's been on my mind.

 I knew he had written a novel "TerrO.R." in the 2000s (super impressive imo, as English is his fourth language) and found myself last night looking at his amazon page only to notice that he wrote another book "Pet Peeves and Possibilities" that he never told us about. I bought and read it last night. It's a collection of short, sweet and humorous essays based on his life.

In one of the essays he writes:

" The Van Gogh Syndrome
 Many painters, sculptors, writers and musicians are so ahead of their times that they go through life undiscovered, depressed, rejected, misunderstood and poor. Van Gogh is a classic example. This artistic genius took his own life in 1890, at the young age of 38, after a life of poverty and frustrations. Had he been frozen in 1890 and defrosted some 50 years later, he might have lived a life as long and as prosperous as Picasso. I begin to think that I also suffer of the Van Gogh Syndrome. Will it be possible for the literary agent who discovers my unpublished manuscripts to press the Defrost button?"

I would love for "Pet Peeves and Possibilities" to suddenly get a spike in attention for his 90th bday, so I had the idea to share in hopes that maybe you'll get it on amazon for the .99 cents he has it listed for, I think it would make his 90th bday truly something special. 

Please share if you're ever so inclined 🙏💗

Today is World Mental Health Day ⁣💚🧠
As a licensed therapist & human who has battled mental illness her entire life, I find today and all days emphasizing mental health, incredibly important 

Approximately 800 million people worldwide have a mental health condition, & that's just diagnosed! 
⁣
There has been amazing progress when it comes to people speaking out, sharing their stories and asking for help⁣
⁣
The stigma on mental illness is starting to decrease and I promise you, the more we shatter the stigma, the more lives will be saved⁣ 💛
⁣
It took me quite a while to share my story. To share my pain. ⁣
⁣
15 years ago to the day I was in the grips of depression, anxiety and ocd. I had no idea that the way I was feeling was a health condition. I thought I had lost my mind. Lost myself. Lost happiness forever. Taking my own life seemed like the only way out. I'm grateful everyday that I mustered up the courage and energy to ask my parents for help.⁣
⁣
I first publicly shared my story in 2014, with a long tumblr post posted to facebook. I felt proud of myself, hoping they were words that could potentially help others to feel less alone. But after reading it, my dad had a different reaction: "you shouldn't post things like that.. what if it impacts you getting a job? what will people think of you knowing you were suicidal?"⁣
⁣
 Those words hurt at the time, but I knew he was wrong. I knew that if a job or a person was to judge me as human based on my illnesses that those weren't the people or jobs for me.⁣
⁣
I've continued to share my story since 2014 because I know that if 15 year old Carly had read someone else's journey of life after debilitating mental illness, it would have given me so much hope. ⁣
⁣
Thankfully, my dad has since changed his views on speaking out ⁣and now understands the importance of normalizing the conversation on mental illness 
⁣
So today, on World Mental Health Day, I encourage you to share your story or to read and learn from others. Mental health IS HEALTH. The more we talk about it the more treatments we will find, the more lives will be saved.
